a jacket is a type of outerwear designed to provide warmth and protection against the elements while offering a stylish appearance. Typically characterized by a front opening, it may feature fastenings such as zippers or buttons and can vary in length, material, and insulation. Jackets can serve various purposes, including casual wear, outdoor activities, or as part of a layered outfit. They come in diverse styles, including but not limited to sporty, classic, or contemporary designs, and may incorporate elements like hoods, pockets, or adjustable features to enhance functionality and comfort. This category encompasses a wide range of options suitable for different weather conditions and personal preferences.

this classification encompasses a category of legwear designed for general use, typically made from flexible materials that provide comfort and ease of movement. These items cover the lower body and are often worn in casual or leisure settings. They can vary in style, fit, and design, ranging from fitted to relaxed silhouettes, and may feature different lengths, such as full-length or cropped. This category excludes formal attire and focuses on versatile, everyday options suitable for various activities. The items classified here are commonly paired with a variety of tops and footwear, making them a staple in casual wardrobes.

work dungarees are specially designed garments characterized by their durable construction and functionality, aimed at providing protection and comfort during various manual tasks. Typically made from robust materials, these garments feature reinforced seams and multiple pockets to accommodate tools and equipment. They are suitable for a range of work environments and activities, offering ease of movement and practicality. The design often includes adjustable straps and a loose fit to enhance flexibility. Unlike other leisure clothing items, work dungarees are tailored to meet the specific demands of labor-intensive tasks while maintaining a casual aesthetic.

this classification encompasses a wide range of outerwear designed for leisure activities, characterized by their casual and comfortable nature. It serves as a collective category that includes various styles and types of garments typically worn for informal occasions. The items classified here are distinguished by their functional and aesthetic attributes, catering to diverse preferences and seasonal requirements. This category may include different fits, materials, and designs, each offering unique features suitable for relaxation or social gatherings. The classification aims to provide a comprehensive overview of leisure outerwear, promoting easy identification and comparison among similar items in the market.

a versatile and stylish outer layer designed for leisure activities, typically characterized by a combination of materials and features that provide comfort and functionality. This type of apparel often includes multiple pockets, adjustable elements, and may incorporate a variety of design elements to enhance usability, making it suitable for casual or active use. The design prioritizes ease of movement and adaptability to varying weather conditions, while maintaining a fashionable appearance. It is distinct from other types of leisure clothing by its specific design and intended use, catering to individuals seeking both practicality and style in their outdoor or casual wear.

a type of outerwear designed primarily for warmth and protection against cold weather. This garment typically features a hood, is insulated, and is often made from water-resistant or waterproof materials. It is characterized by a loose fit, providing ease of movement, and may include additional features such as pockets, zippers, and adjustable cuffs to enhance functionality and comfort. This style is commonly worn in casual settings and is suitable for various outdoor activities, offering both style and practical utility for the wearer.

a shirt is a type of upper-body garment characterized by a collar, sleeves, and a front opening, typically fastened with buttons or other closures. It is designed to be worn on its own or layered under other clothing items. Shirts can be made from various fabrics and may come in numerous styles, patterns, and colors, catering to diverse occasions and personal preferences. This attire is often associated with casual or semi-formal settings and can be tailored for comfort or fashion. The design and fit of shirts can vary widely, including options such as fitted, loose, long-sleeved, short-sleeved, or sleeveless, making them a versatile choice for everyday wear.

a pullover is a type of upper-body garment typically characterized by its knit construction, which is designed to be worn by slipping it over the head. This apparel is usually made from various materials including wool, cotton, or synthetic fibers, providing warmth and comfort. It can feature various styles such as crew neck, v-neck, or turtleneck, and may come in different lengths and fits. Pullovers are often considered casual wear and can be worn alone or layered over other clothing items. Their versatility allows them to be suitable for various occasions, ranging from leisure activities to more relaxed social settings.

a specific type of wearable item designed primarily for professional or specialized use, characterized by its knitted or woven fabric that provides warmth and comfort. This apparel typically features a long-sleeved design and may vary in style, color, and material to suit various occupational needs. It is intended for use in work environments where both functionality and adherence to professional appearance are important. This item may also be utilized in settings that require a uniform appearance, ensuring that the wearer maintains a cohesive and identifiable look while performing their duties.

a type of apparel designed specifically for professional or operational use, typically worn by individuals in various service industries. This item is characterized by its tailored fit and functional design, offering comfort and practicality while adhering to specific standards of appearance. It serves to enhance the professionalism of the wearer while providing an appropriate level of mobility and ease of movement. The garment may be made from durable materials to withstand the demands of service-related tasks and is often designed to complement other service-oriented attire.

this classification refers to a type of apparel designed specifically for service-related functions, characterized by its utility and durability. The item is typically worn around the waist and serves both functional and aesthetic purposes, often equipped with various features to enhance usability in professional settings. Its design may accommodate tools or equipment, providing practical support while maintaining a professional appearance. This classification distinguishes itself from other wearables by focusing on the unique attributes that cater to service duties, ensuring comfort and ease of movement for individuals engaged in various occupational roles.

a type of apparel designed specifically for use in service-oriented environments, typically characterized by its professional appearance and functionality. This type of clothing is often made from durable, easy-to-clean materials to withstand the demands of various service roles. It may feature specific design elements that cater to the needs of service workers, such as pockets for tools or equipment, and is intended to provide comfort and mobility while maintaining a polished look. The design may vary to fulfill different roles within the service industry, ensuring that the wearer presents a professional image while performing their duties.

this classification encompasses a variety of trousers specifically designed for professional or work-related purposes. These garments are crafted to meet the functional demands of various occupations, providing durability, comfort, and practicality. The design may incorporate features such as reinforced stitching, pockets for tools or personal items, and materials that enhance wear resistance. This category distinguishes itself from other related apparel by focusing on lower body coverage, ensuring that individuals are equipped with appropriate attire for their tasks while maintaining a professional appearance.

a type of outerwear designed specifically for use in professional or operational environments, providing both functionality and protection. This apparel is typically crafted from durable materials to withstand wear and tear while ensuring comfort and mobility. It may feature elements such as pockets, adjustable cuffs, and closures that cater to the demands of various service-related tasks. This item is intended for individuals engaged in specialized roles requiring distinct attire that meets both safety standards and operational requirements, distinguishing it from other similar apparel designed for specific purposes or functions within the same category of service-related clothing.

This type of clothing is crafted to meet specific functional requirements, providing protection from environmental elements, enhancing safety, or fulfilling uniform standards. The materials used are often durable and may include features such as moisture-wicking, breathability, or impact resistance. This category encompasses a variety of styles, including caps, helmets, and other headwear that serve practical purposes while maintaining compliance with industry regulations or organizational policies.

a necktie designed specifically for use in professional or formal service environments. This apparel accessory is typically made from fabric and serves to complement formal attire, enhancing the overall appearance of the wearer. Neckties may vary in style, color, and pattern, allowing for personal expression while adhering to service uniform standards. They are an essential component of many service-related dress codes, providing a polished and cohesive look for individuals in various professional roles.

It is primarily intended for use in professional settings where both functionality and compliance with safety or uniform standards are required. The design may include additional elements such as pockets, zippers, and adjustable components to enhance comfort and utility. This clothing item is suitable for individuals engaged in outdoor or demanding work environments, ensuring they remain comfortable while performing their duties.

a type of wearable item designed specifically for use in professional or service-oriented environments, typically featuring a sleeveless design to allow for ease of movement and comfort. This item is often made from durable materials to withstand various working conditions and may include practical elements such as pockets or fastening mechanisms. It serves both functional and aesthetic purposes, providing a uniform appearance while also catering to the specific needs of individuals engaged in service-related activities. This category is distinct from other wearable items intended for similar environments, each tailored for specific roles and requirements within the service sector.

Overcoat is a type of long coat intended to be worn as the outermost garment, which usually extends below the knee. Overcoats are most commonly used in winter when warmth is more important. They are sometimes confused with or referred to as topcoats, which are shorter and end at or above the knees. Topcoats and overcoats together are known as outercoats. Unlike overcoats, topcoats are usually made from lighter weight cloth such as gabardine or covert, while overcoats are made from heavier cloth or fur

Pea coat (or peacoat, pea jacket, pilot jacket, reefer jacket) is an outer coat, generally of a navy-coloured heavy wool, originally worn by sailors of European and later American navies. Pea coats are characterized by short length, broad lapels, double-breasted fronts, often large wooden, metal or plastic buttons, and vertical or slash pockets. References to the pea jacket appear in American newspapers at least as early as the 1720s, and modern renditions still maintain the original design and composition
Capuchon (from French capuchon, hood) is a short women's coat with a large hood
Crombie is a classic English city coat, tailored from thick wool fabric, usually single-breasted with concealed button placket. This coat symbolizes working class

Duffel coat (also duffle coat, for example in Canada) is a coat made from duffel, a coarse, thick, woolen material. The name derives from Duffel, a town in the province of Antwerp in Belgium where the fabric originated. Duffel bags were originally made from the same material. The hood and toggle fastenings proved popular, and the coat spread across Europe by the 1850s. By 1890 it was being supplied to the British Royal Navy. After World War II, the coats became available as government surplus stock and became popular, especially with students

Vinyl coats are made of coated fabrics (PU or PVC). The varnish can be gloss varnish or matt varnish. Matt varnish is also used in the sports sector for rain jackets and rain suits. The first vinyl coats were women's coats, they replaced the classic raincoat. Most recently, they served less as a functional garment and more as a fashion accessory. Classic patent coats are black, red or white, today retailers supply all shades. Glossy varnish, similar to nappa leather, is attributed an erotic charisma

Loden cape is an overcoat of Tyrolean origin, made of a thick, water-resistant woolen material with a short pile known as loden cloth, first produced by peasants in Austria. This fabric is derived from the coarse, oily wool of mountain sheep and has a traditional earthy green colour. The name is derived from Middle High German 'lode' or from Old High German 'lodo', meaning 'coarse cloth'. It is a cloth of traditional Tracht worn in both Austrian and German Tyrol

Fur coat is called a garment made by a furrier from animal skins in the cut of a coat. The hair side of the fur can be on the outside or on the inside (with the leather side on the outside). Textile coats lined with fur - about since before 1900, when modern fur fashion began to create furs with the hair on the outside - are usually no longer called fur coats

Poncho is an outer garment designed to keep the body warm. A rain poncho is made from a watertight material designed to keep the body dry from the rain. Ponchos have been used by the Native American peoples of the Andes since pre-Hispanic time, from places now under the territory of Ecuador, Colombia, Bolivia, Argentina, Chile and Peru and are now considered typical South American garments

Raincoat or slicker is a waterproof or water-resistant coat worn to protect the body from rain. The term rain jacket is sometimes used to refer to raincoats that are waist length. A rain jacket may be combined with a pair of rain pants to make a rain suit. A rain suit may also be in one piece like a boilersuit. Modern raincoats are often constructed from waterproof fabrics that are breathable, such as Gore-Tex or Tyvek and coated nylons. These fabrics allow water vapour to pass through, allowing the garment to 'breathe' so that the sweat of the wearer can escape. The amount of pouring rain a raincoat can handle is sometimes measured in the unit millimetres, water gauge

Trench coat or trenchcoat is a coat variety made of waterproof heavy-duty cotton gabardine drill, leather, or poplin. It generally has a removable insulated lining, raglan sleeves, and the classic versions come in various lengths ranging from just above the ankles (the longest) to above the knee (the shortest). It was originally an item of clothing for Army officers (developed before the war but adapted for use in the trenches of the First World War, hence its name) and shows this influence in its styling

Ulster is a Victorian working daytime overcoat, with a cape and sleeves. The Ulster is distinguished from the Inverness by the length of the cape. In the Ulster, this cape only reaches the elbows, allowing free movement of the forearms. It was commonly worn by coachmen who would be seated outdoors in bad weather for long periods, but needed to use their arms to hold reins. Often made of hard-wearing fabrics, such as herringbones or tweeds, it was not a formal coat at the time, though in the 20th century a cape would be seen as such. After the Edwardian period, it lost its cape, and continued to be used as a heavy-duty overcoat, often in a double-breasted style

a specialized protective item designed to maintain a controlled environment by minimizing contamination risks during handling processes. This item is typically made from materials that provide both barrier protection and dexterity, allowing the wearer to perform tasks while ensuring cleanliness. It is commonly used in sterile settings, such as laboratories, manufacturing areas, and medical facilities, where the integrity of the environment is critical. The design often includes features that enhance comfort and fit, as well as the capability to be disposed of or sanitized after use, thereby supporting hygiene protocols.

this category encompasses specialized apparel designed for use in environments that require controlled levels of contamination. The items within this classification are typically constructed from materials that minimize particle release and are easy to clean or dispose of. These garments are crucial for maintaining sterile conditions in industries such as pharmaceuticals, biotechnology, and electronics manufacturing. The design focuses on providing comfort and mobility while ensuring compliance with stringent cleanliness standards. Unlike other related apparel, this specific type is tailored to cover the lower body, offering protection and maintaining hygiene in sensitive operational areas.

a specialized garment designed for use in controlled environments where cleanliness and contamination control are paramount. This attire is typically made from non-linting, breathable materials that offer protection against particulate contamination while allowing for comfort and mobility. It is tailored to fit securely, preventing the ingress of contaminants and ensuring the wearer's skin is covered. This type of clothing is essential in industries such as pharmaceuticals, biotechnology, and electronics, where strict adherence to cleanliness protocols is required to maintain the integrity of sterile processes and products. The design may include features such as elastic cuffs, adjustable closures, and anti-static properties, catering to the specific needs of cleanroom operations.

a type of protective garment designed specifically for use in controlled environments, ensuring minimal contamination and maintaining cleanliness. This attire typically covers the entire body, providing a barrier against particulate matter and microbial contaminants. It is constructed from materials that meet stringent hygiene standards and is often designed for single-use or easy decontamination. The garment is tailored to fit securely and comfortably, allowing for ease of movement while safeguarding the wearer and the surrounding environment from potential pollutants. This clothing item is essential in industries such as pharmaceuticals, biotechnology, and electronics, where contamination control is critical to operational integrity and product quality.

a specialized protective footwear item designed to be worn in controlled environments where contamination prevention is critical. This type of footwear is typically made from non-woven materials that minimize particle shedding and can be easily disposed of or cleaned. It ensures that personnel maintain cleanliness standards while performing tasks in sensitive areas, such as laboratories, manufacturing plants, or healthcare facilities. The design often includes features that promote ease of use, comfort, and safety, providing a barrier against contaminants while allowing for necessary mobility.

a cleanroom hood is a specialized head covering designed to maintain a controlled environment by minimizing contamination from hair and skin particles. It is typically made from non-linting, breathable materials that offer comfort while ensuring effective barrier protection. This type of hood is essential in environments where cleanliness is critical, such as laboratories, semiconductor manufacturing, and pharmaceutical production. The design may include features like elastic openings for a snug fit, anti-static properties, and compatibility with other cleanroom attire. It serves as an integral part of personal protective equipment, ensuring compliance with stringent cleanliness standards required in sensitive operational settings.

Dress (also known as a frock or a gown) is a garment traditionally worn by women or girls consisting of a skirt with an attached bodice (or a matching bodice giving the effect of a one-piece garment). It consists of a top piece that covers the torso and hangs down over the legs. A dress can be any one-piece garment containing a skirt of any length, and can be formal or casual. A dress can have sleeves, straps, or be held up with elastic around the chest, leaving the shoulders bare
Evening gown, evening dress or gown is a long flowing, full-length dress usually worn at formal occasions
Maxi dresses - maxi is a term used since the late 1960s for ankle-length, typically informal dresses
Midi dress - a 'midi' is used to refer to any dress or skirt that has a hem which hits at mid-calf - halfway between the knee and ankle
Knee length dress - hemline ends at knee height
Mini dress - a very short dress that terminates above the knee
Micro dress is an extremely short version of a mini

a type of accessory designed to cover and protect the head, typically characterized by a structured or unstructured form, varying styles, and materials. This category encompasses various designs that may serve aesthetic, functional, or seasonal purposes, including but not limited to items that provide shade from the sun, warmth in colder weather, or simply a fashion statement. These accessories can range from casual to formal styles and may include adjustable features to accommodate different head sizes. The classification excludes specialized items focused on specific protective functions or those designed for particular activities, emphasizing a general use in everyday wear.

a headband is a flexible band worn around the forehead, typically used to keep hair away from the face or to absorb sweat during physical activities. It can be made from various materials such as fabric, rubber, or elastic, and may come in different styles and designs. Headbands can serve both functional and decorative purposes, being utilized in sports, fitness, or as a fashion accessory. They may also feature various embellishments or patterns, allowing for personal expression while providing comfort and practicality during use.

a protective item designed to cover the face and neck, offering insulation and shielding against cold weather conditions. This accessory is typically made from warm, flexible materials to ensure comfort while effectively blocking wind and retaining heat. It is specifically tailored for use in low-temperature environments, making it ideal for outdoor activities in winter. The design may include features such as adjustable elements for a secure fit, breathability options to prevent moisture buildup, and additional coverings to protect the ears and face. This item is distinct in its purpose and construction, serving as a specialized solution for cold weather protection.

a protective headwear item designed specifically to shield the head from various environmental factors while providing comfort and style. This category encompasses products that offer essential coverage, often featuring adjustable elements for a secure fit. The design may include materials that enhance durability and breathability, catering to both functional and aesthetic preferences. These items are typically worn during outdoor activities or casual settings, providing a balance of protection and fashion. They are distinguished from other headwear types by their specific protective features and intended use, ensuring they serve a unique purpose in personal attire.

This apparel is generally worn as part of a collective identity, often featuring unique patterns, colors, or embellishments that reflect the values or heritage of a particular group. It is designed to provide comfort and ease of movement while often adhering to customary styles. The design may vary based on cultural or organizational standards, and they are distinguished from other types of similar attire by their unique features, such as cut, embellishments, or color schemes.

jacket is a garment for the upper body, usually extending below the hips. A jacket typically has sleeves, and fastens in the front or slightly on the side. A jacket is generally lighter, tighter-fitting, and less insulating than a coat, which is outerwear. Some jackets are fashionable, while others serve as protective clothing. Jackets without sleeves are vests

Anorak is a type of coat with a hood, often lined with fur or faux fur. The Caribou Inuit invented this kind of garment, originally made from caribou or seal skin, for hunting and kayaking in the frigid Arctic. Some Inuit anoraks require regular coating with fish oil to retain their water resistance. The words anorak and parka have been used interchangeably, but they are somewhat different garments. Strictly speaking, an anorak is a waterproof, hooded, pull-over jacket without a front opening, and sometimes drawstrings at the waist and cuffs, and a parka is a hip-length cold-weather coat, typically stuffed with down or very warm synthetic fiber, and with a fur-lined hood

Suit jacket, also called a lounge jacket, lounge coat or suit coat, is a jacket in classic menswear that is part of a suit. Most single-breasted suits have two or three buttons, and one or four buttons are unusual (except that tuxedo dinner jackets often have only one button). It is rare to find a suit with more than four buttons, although zoot suits can have as many as six or more due to their longer length. There is also variation in the placement and style of buttons, since the button placement is critical to the overall impression of height conveyed by the jacket. The sportier variant is also called blazer

Blouson or blouse jacket is a jacket that is drawn tight at the waist, causing it to blouse out and hang over the waistband. Some of them have a hood. It takes most of its modern traits from the American flight jacket and police blouson. It is related to the Eisenhower jacket. It is considered to be both sportswear and casual civilian clothing

Leather jacket is a jacket-length coat that is usually worn on top of other apparel or item of clothing, and made from the tanned hide of various animals. The leather material is typically dyed black, or various shades of brown, but a wide range of colors is possible. Leather jackets can be designed for many purposes, and specific styles have been associated with subcultures such as greasers, rednecks, cowboys, motorcyclists, military aviators, mobsters, police, secret agents, and music subcultures (punks, goths, metalheads, rivetheads), who have worn the garment for protective or fashionable reasons, and occasionally to create a potentially intimidating appearance

Quilted jacket like a down jacket or puffer jacket is a quilted, padded jacket filled with down feathers (usually duck or goose down). This material is usually used to insulate an outer layer which is usually some synthetic fiber such as nylon or polyester

Cardigan is a type of knitted garment that has an open front. Commonly cardigans have buttons: garments that are tied are instead considered a robe. A more modern version of the garment has no buttons and hangs open by design. By contrast, a pullover (or sweater) does not open in front but must be 'pulled over' the head to be worn. It may be machine- or hand-knitted. Traditionally, cardigans were made of wool but can now be made of cotton, synthetic fibers, or any combination thereof

Pulled over the head sweater, also called a jumper in British English, is a piece of clothing, typically with long sleeves, made of knitted or crocheted material, that covers the upper part of the body. When sleeveless, the garment is often called a slipover or sweater vest. Oxford University states that in British usage sweaters are always pulled over the head and jumpers are not necessarily, whereas most or all other British dictionaries disagree and say that sweaters are not necessarily pullovers or even say that jumpers are always pullovers, i.e. never open in front

When sleeveless, the garment is often called a slipover or sweater vest. Oxford University states that in British usage sweaters are always pulled over the head and jumpers are not necessarily, whereas most or all other British dictionaries disagree and say that sweaters are not necessarily pullovers or even say that jumpers are always pullovers, i.e. never open in front

Sweatshirt is a type of sweater that is made of a fabric similar to sweatpants. A sweatshirt worn with sweatpants forms a sweatsuit, an exercise outfit designed to raise the core body temperature and cause perspiration in order to lose body weight before a weigh-in for a weight-divided sport. It is fashioned out of a thick, usually cotton jersey material.[citation needed] Sweatshirts are also almost exclusively casual attire and hence not as dressy as some sweaters. Sweatshirts may or may not have a hood. A sweatshirt with a hood is now usually referred to as a hoodie, although more formal media still use the term 'hooded sweatshirt'

Polo shirt is a form of shirt with a collar, a placket neckline with two or three buttons, and an optional pocket. Polo shirts are usually short sleeved, they were used by polo players originally in India in 1859 and in Great Britain during the 1920s. Polo shirts are usually made of knitted cotton (rather than woven cloth), usually a piqu knit, or less commonly an interlock knit (the latter used frequently, though not exclusively, with pima cotton polos), or using other fibers such as silk, merino wool, synthetic fibers, or blends of natural and synthetic fibers. A dress-length version of the shirt is called a polo dress

T-shirt, or tee shirt, is a style of fabric shirt named after the T shape of its body and sleeves. Traditionally, it has short sleeves and a round neckline, known as a crew neck, which lacks a collar. T-shirts are generally made of a stretchy, light and inexpensive fabric and are easy to clean
Tricot or unitard is a skintight, one-piece garment with long legs and sometimes long sleeves, usually stopping at the wrists and ankles. It differs from a leotard which does not have long legs

Top is an item of clothing that covers at least the chest, but which usually covers most of the upper human body between the neck and the waistline. The bottom of tops can be as short as mid-torso, or as long as mid-thigh. Men's tops are generally paired with pants, and women's with pants or skirts. Common types of tops are t-shirts, blouses and shirts

Sweater vest (known as a tank top or sleeveless sweater in the UK) is an item of knitwear that is similar to a sweater, but without sleeves, usually with a low-cut neckline. They were popular in the 20th century, particularly in the 1970s in the UK, and are again growing in popularity in this century

a type of garment designed to be worn close to the skin, typically under outer clothing, that provides coverage and comfort. It is characterized by its lightweight fabric and form-fitting design, often featuring short sleeves or no sleeves at all. This clothing item serves both functional and aesthetic purposes, ensuring modesty while contributing to the overall outfit. It is commonly made from soft materials to enhance comfort and may vary in style, color, and pattern. This garment is distinct from other intimate apparel in its specific role and design, focusing on upper body coverage.

a type of garment designed for wearing under outer clothing, specifically tailored to cover the lower body. This item is typically made from soft, breathable materials for comfort and is intended for everyday use. It serves both practical purposes, such as providing support and coverage, and aesthetic appeal, often available in various styles, colors, and patterns. This category excludes similar items like tops or full-body garments, focusing solely on those designed for the lower torso, ensuring distinct functionality and design characteristics.

this classification encompasses a specific category of outer garments designed for comfort and leisure, typically worn over other clothing. These items are characterized by their loose fit, durability, and versatility, making them suitable for various casual settings. The primary function of these garments is to provide ease of movement while protecting the underlying clothing from dirt or wear. In the military, hats may denote nationality, branch of service, rank or regiment.[3] Police typically wear distinctive hats such as peaked caps or brimmed hats, such as those worn by the Royal Canadian Mounted Police

Knit cap, originally of wool (though now often of synthetic fibers), is designed to provide warmth in cold weather. Typically, the knit cap is of simple, tapering constructions, though many variants exist. Historically, the wool knit cap was an extremely common form of headgear for seamen, fishers, hunters and others spending their working day outdoors from the 18th century and forward, and is still commonly used for this purpose in the northern regions of North America, Europe, Asia, and other cold regions of the world. Being found all over the world where climate demands a warm hat, the knit cap can be found under a multitude of local names

Cap is a form of headgear. Caps have crowns that fit very close to the head. They made their first appearance as early as 3,200BC. Caps typically have a visor or no brim at all. Caps are more popular in casual and informal settings, and you will notice them in sports and fashion. All genders and ages enjoy wearing caps. They are typically designed for warmth, and often incorporate a visor to block sunlight from the eyes. They come in many shapes, sizes, and are of different brands. Baseball caps are one of the most common headgear caps. Until 1954 baseball players could pick any kind of cap they wanted, just to keep the sun out of their eyes. Glove is a garment covering the whole hand. Gloves usually have separate sheaths or openings for each finger and the thumb. If there is an opening but no (or a short) covering sheath for each finger they are called fingerless gloves. Fingerless gloves having one small opening rather than individual openings for each finger are sometimes called gauntlets, though gauntlets are not necessarily fingerless

Necktie, or simply a tie, is a long piece of cloth, worn, usually by men, for decorative purposes around the neck, resting under the shirt collar and knotted at the throat. Variants include the ascot, bow, bolo, zipper, cravat, and knit. The modern necktie, ascot, and bow tie are descended from the cravat. Neckties are generally unsized, but may be available in a longer size. In some cultures men and boys wear neckties as part of regular office attire or formal wear

Scarf is a piece of fabric worn around the neck or head for warmth, sun protection, cleanliness, fashion, or religious reasons or used to show the support for a sports club or team. They can be made in a variety of different materials such as wool, linen, silk or cotton. It is a common type of neckwear

Suspenders are typically attached to trousers with clips or buttons using leather tabs at the ends

Umbrella or parasol is a folding canopy supported by wooden or metal ribs that is usually mounted on a wooden, metal, or plastic pole. It is designed to protect a person against rain or sunlight. The term umbrella is traditionally used when protecting oneself from rain, with parasol used when protecting oneself from sunlight, though the terms continue to be used interchangeably. Often the difference is the material used for the canopy. Some parasols are not waterproof. Umbrella canopies may be made of fabric or flexible plastic. There are also combinations of parasol and umbrella that are called en-tout-cas (French for 'in any case')

It is distinguished from the boot by the height of the shaft, which reaches a maximum of the arch of the foot at the front and below the ankle of the foot at the side. It is worn in dry, cool to warm weather and is therefore the most worn type of shoe from spring to autumn

Originally, a lace-up shoe is a shoe whose closure is closed (laced) by means of thin leather straps or laces. Nowadays, other closure methods exist, such as Velcro. Basically, the closure gives the shoe a firm hold on the foot, which - also depending on the shaft cut (leaf cut or derby cut) of the shoe in question - can be comfortably varied in width to accommodate different foot shapes and uses. Lace-up shoes are also called lace-ups in the trade

Sneakers (also called trainers, athletic shoes, tennis shoes, gym shoes, kicks, sport shoes, flats, running shoes, or runners) are shoes primarily designed for sports or other forms of physical exercise but that are now also widely used for everyday casual wear

Bag is a container and transport aid made of more or less flexible material for transporting goods. Bags usually have handles, handles or other devices to hold them by hand or otherwise carry and carry them on the body. Bags are usually made of textiles, flexible plastic, leather or paper. In addition to bags that are carried in the hand or in the crook of the arm, there are also those that are carried by means of straps, cords or belt(s) on the back, in front of the chest, in front of the abdomen and in many other places, or are strapped around parts of the body by means of straps (e.g. fanny packs strapped around the hips or waist)

These are bags with a long strap or belt so that the strap can be worn over one shoulder. There are two carrying variants: In the first variant, the strap runs diagonally across the chest and back starting from one shoulder, so that the actual bag is worn on the other side of the body or in the area of the diagonal in the chest or back. In the other variation of carrying a shoulder bag, the strap runs vertically parallel to one side of the body, so that the actual bag then usually dangles relatively loosely at about hip level (or higher or lower, depending on the strap length). Sports bags and travel bags are often offered as shoulder bags, but so are handbags and cotton shopping bags. Fanny packs are sometimes worn as shoulder bags instead of belt bags

Briefcase is a narrow hard-sided box-shaped bag or case used mainly for carrying papers and equipped with a handle. Lawyers commonly use briefcases to carry briefs to present to a court, hence the name. Businesspeople and other white collar professionals also use briefcases to carry papers, and since the 1980s, electronic devices such as laptop computers and tablet computers. Some briefcases have only a main internal space, while others may have subsections, accordion sections, small pockets, or dividers. Briefcases may be made from leather, vinyl, durable fabric, thin metal (such as aluminium), or plastic. Leather, vinyl, or fabric briefcases may have externally-accessible pockets or sleeves in addition to the main storage space. Some briefcases made of fabric may have a shoulder strap. Briefcases typically have a lock to protect the contents. Nowadays, briefcases may have padded internal pouches to protect laptop computers

Flight bag can refer to any baggage taken on board a flight, but usually refers to a specific type of document bag carried by pilots and flight crews. Often adorned with an airline logo, at one time the flight bag was a chic fashion accessory

Travel bags are part of the luggage. They are used especially to transport clothes when traveling. Travel bags usually have a long slot-like opening in the upper part of the bag, which can be greatly widened

Sports bag is used to transport sports clothing, drinks and, if necessary, care products. Depending on the type of sport and intended use, different variants are used in terms of size, shape and material. A sports bag is often made of water-repellent and insensitive materials and has additional (side) compartments that make it easier to pack and find utensils or to store sweaty clothes. Students also use sports bags to carry the clothes they need for physical education classes

School bags (satchels) are used by students to carry their binders, books and other school supplies. They are made of sturdy material and have a large flap closure with buckles. Often they also have side compartments for drinks, snacks, etc

Handbag, commonly known as a purse in North American English, is a handled medium-to-large bag used to carry personal items. The term 'purse' originally referred to a small bag for holding coins. In many English-speaking countries it is still used to refer to a small money bag. A 'handbag' is a larger accessory that holds objects beyond currency, such as personal items. American English typically uses the terms purse and handbag interchangeably. The term handbag began appearing in the early 1900s. Initially, it was most often used to refer to men's hand-luggage. Women's bags grew larger and more complex during this period, and the term was attached to the accessory 'Pocketbook' is another term for a woman's hand bag that was most commonly used on the East Coast of the United States in the mid-twentieth century

Messenger bag (also called a courier bag) is a type of sack, usually made of cloth (natural or synthetic). It is worn over one shoulder with a strap that goes across the chest resting the bag on the lower back. While messenger bags are sometimes used by couriers, they are now also an urban fashion icon. Some types of messenger bags are called carryalls. A smaller version is often called a sling bag

Backpack - also called knapsack, rucksack, rucksac, pack, sackpack, booksack, bookbag or backsack - is, in its simplest frameless form, a cloth sack carried on one's back and secured with two straps that go over the shoulders, but it can have an external frame, internal frame, and there are bodypacks. Backpacks are commonly used by hikers and students, and are often preferred to handbags for carrying heavy loads or carrying any sort of equipment, because of the limited capacity to carry heavy weights for long periods of time in the hands

Chest pouch is a small, flat bag worn around the neck with a strap, ribbon or string. It is often used to store valuables (money, papers). Sometimes it is worn under the outer clothing for security reasons

Suitcase is a form of luggage. It is often a somewhat flat, rectangular-shaped bag with rounded square corners, either metal, hard plastic or made of cloth, vinyl or leather that more or less retains its shape. Vinyl, leather or cloth suitcases may have a metal frame. It has a carrying handle on one side and is used mainly for transporting clothes, toiletries and other small possessions during trips. Hardshell suitcases open on hinges like a door. Suitcases may lock with keys or a combination

Toiletry bag (also called a toiletry kit, ditty bag, dopp kit, bathroom kit, sponge bag, toilet bag, toilet kit, body hygiene kit, travel kit, wash bag, shaving kit, or wet pack) is a portable container - usually a pouch with a drawstring or zippered closure - which holds body hygiene and toiletry supplies such as toothbrush and toothpaste, dental floss, cotton swabs, deodorant, nail clippers, tweezers, soap, shaving supplies, hair brush, tampons, contact lenses and supplies, and similar items while travelling and in other circumstances where permanent shelves and cupboards are unavailable or impractical for use

Wallet is a chest-pocket sized, usually foldable, flat container for IDs, paper money, folded documents and others. A wallet was originally used to carry its owner's letters. Then, after the introduction of paper money, it was also used to store banknotes. Wallets are made of leather, sometimes textile fabric, and are often carried in the inner breast pockets of men's jackets

Purse or pouch (from the Latin bursa, which in turn is from the Greek), sometimes called coin purse for clarity, is a small money bag or pouch, made for carrying coins. In most Commonwealth countries it is known simply as a purse, while 'purse' in the United States usually refers to a handbag. 'Purse' can also be a synonym to bursary (which has the same origin), i.e. a monetary prize in a competition

Belly bag (American English) or waist bag, fanny pack (US), belt bag, moon bag or bumbag (British English) is a small fabric pouch worn like a belt around the waist by use of a strap above the hips that is secured usually with some sort of buckle. The straps sometimes have tri-glide slides, making them adjustable in order to fit properly. It can be considered as a purse worn around the waist

Jewellery or jewelry (American English, see spelling differences) consists of decorative items worn for personal adornment, such as brooches, rings, necklaces, earrings, pendants, bracelets, and cufflinks. Jewellery may be attached to the body or the clothes

Necklace is an article of jewellery that is worn around the neck. Necklaces may have been one of the earliest types of adornment worn by humans. They often serve ceremonial, religious, magical, or funerary purposes and are also used as symbols of wealth and status, given that they are commonly made of precious metals and stones

Bracelet is an article of jewellery that is worn around the wrist. Bracelets may serve different uses, such as being worn as an ornament. When worn as ornaments, bracelets may have a supportive function to hold other items of decoration, such as charms. Medical and identity information are marked on some bracelets, such as allergy bracelets, hospital patient-identification tags, and bracelet tags for newborn babies. Bracelets may be worn to signify a certain phenomenon, such as breast cancer awareness, or for religious/cultural purposes

Ring is a round band, usually of metal, worn as ornamental jewellery. The term 'ring' by itself always denotes jewellery worn on the finger. When worn as an ornament elsewhere, the body part is specified within the term, e.g., earrings, neck rings, arm rings, and toe rings. Rings always fit snugly around or in the part of the body they ornament, so bands worn loosely, like a bracelet, are not rings. Rings may be made of almost any hard material: wood, bone, stone, metal, glass, gemstone or plastic. They may be set with gemstones (diamond, ruby, sapphire or emerald) or with other types of stone or glass

Earring is a piece of jewelry worn on the ear. It is attached either through an ear hole in the ear or as an ear clip on the ear lobe. Earrings were and are worn by all genders in many cultures around the world, but more often by women. Several special piercings are possible on the nose. Above all, the nostril piercing through the wing of the nose has established itself, which is usually meant when talking about a 'nose ring'. From the hippie culture it was first adopted from India to the Western cultural sphere

Watch is a portable timepiece intended to be carried or worn by a person. It is designed to keep a consistent movement despite the motions caused by the person's activities. A wristwatch is designed to be worn around the wrist, attached by a watch strap or other type of bracelet, including metal bands, leather straps or any other kind of bracelet. A pocket watch is designed for a person to carry in a pocket, often attached to a chain

Watch strap, watch band, watch bracelet or watch belt is a bracelet that straps a wrist watch onto the wrist. Watch straps may be made of leather, plastic, rubber, cloth, or metal, sometimes in combination. It can be regarded as a fashion item, serving both a utilitarian and decorative function. Some metal watch straps may be plated with, or even in rare cases made of, precious metals

Undershirt in American English (vest in British and Indian English), is an article of underwear worn underneath a dress shirt intended to protect it from body sweat and odors. It can have short sleeves (T-shirt) or be sleeveless (A-shirt). The term most commonly refers to upper-body innerwear worn by males. An undershirt/ vest may be worn to protect the body from stiff or otherwise uncomfortable fabric. It also makes dress shirts less transparent, to reduce the amount of sweat absorbed by the shirt's fabric. It can be worn during winter months as an extra layer of warmth, and reduces wear on the upper layers of clothing

Ballet flats are women's shoes for everyday wear which are similar to/inspired by a women's ballet shoes, with a very thin heel or the appearance of no heel at all. The style sometimes features a ribbon-like binding around the low tops of the slipper and may have a slight gathering at the top-front of the vamp (toe box) and sometimes a tiny, decorative string tie. Ballet slippers can be adjusted and tightened to the wearer's foot by means of this string tie

High or stiletto heel, or just stiletto, is a shoe with a long, thin, high heel. It is named after the stiletto dagger. High or stiletto heels may vary in length from 2.5 centimetres (1 inch) to 25 cm (10 inches) or more if a platform sole is used, and are sometimes defined as having a diameter at the ground of less than 1 cm (slightly less than half an inch). Stiletto-style heels 5 cm (2.0 in) or shorter are called kitten heels
Slippers are light footwear that are easy to put on and off and are intended to be worn indoors, particularly at home

Moccasin is a shoe, made of deerskin or other soft leather, consisting of a sole (made with leather that has not been 'worked') and sides made of one piece of leather, stitched together at the top, and sometimes with a vamp (additional panel of leather). The sole is soft and flexible and the upper part often is adorned with embroidery or beading. Though sometimes worn inside, it is chiefly intended for outdoor use. Historically, it is the footwear of many indigenous people of North America. Moreover, hunters, traders, and European settlers wore them

Slip-ons are typically low, lace-less shoes. The style which is most commonly seen, known as a loafer or slippers in American culture, has a moccasin construction. One of the first designs was introduced in London by Wildsmith Shoes, called the Wildsmith Loafer. They began as casual shoes, but have increased in popularity to the point of being worn in America with business suits. Another design was introduced as Aurlandskoen (the Aurland Shoe) in Norway (early 20th century). They are worn in many situations in a variety of colors and designs, often featuring tassels on the front, or metal decorations (the 'Gucci' loafer)

Boot, plural boots, is a type of specific footwear. Most boots mainly cover the foot and the ankle, while some also cover some part of the lower calf. Some boots extend up the leg, sometimes as far as the knee or even the hip. Most boots have a heel that is clearly distinguishable from the rest of the sole, even if the two are made of one piece. Traditionally made of leather or rubber, modern boots are made from a variety of materials. Boots are worn both for their functionality - protecting the foot and leg from water, extreme cold, mud or hazards or providing additional ankle support for strenuous activities with added traction requirements (e.g., hiking), or may have hobnails on their undersides to protect against wear and to get better grip and for reasons of style and fashion

If it is an ankle-high boot (lace-up boot, slip-on boot with elastic insert or with a zipper), it is also called an ankle boot. The type of construction (= production-related construction method of the connection of shaft and sole), different soles and heel heights are irrelevant. In the narrower sense, an ankle boot is an elegant boot with an elastic insert on the side of the shaft that makes it easier to slip on and keeps the boot on the foot

Rubber boots or Wellington boot was originally a type of leather boot adapted from Hessian boots, a style of military riding boot. They were worn and popularised by Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington. The 'Wellington' boot became a staple of practical foot wear for the British aristocracy and middle class in the early 19th century. The name was subsequently given to waterproof boots made of rubber and they are no longer associated with a particular class. They are now commonly used for a range of agricultural and outdoors pursuits

Over-the-knee boots (or cuissardes, which include thighboots, top boots, hip-boots, and waders), OTK boots, are long boots that fully or partly cover the knee. Originally created as a man's riding boot in the 15th century, in the latter part of the 20th century, the style was redefined as a fashion boot for women. Over-the-knee boots are also used as a work boot in circumstances requiring additional protection for the legs (e.g. fishing waders)

Sandals are an open type of footwear, consisting of a sole held to the wearer's foot by straps going over the instep and around the ankle. Sandals can also have a heel. While the distinction between sandals and other types of footwear can sometimes be blurry (as in the case of huaraches - the woven leather footwear seen in Mexico, and peep-toe pumps), the common understanding is that a sandal leaves all or most of the foot exposed. People may choose to wear sandals for several reasons, among them comfort in warm weather, economy (sandals tend to require less material than shoes and are usually easier to construct), and as a fashion choice

Water shoe is a type of footwear that is typically used for activities where the feet are likely to become wet, such as kayaking. Water shoes are usually made of mesh and have a hard sole used to prevent cuts and abrasions when walking in wet, rocky environments. They may often have tiny holes on the bottom or sides of the sole to allow for quick water drainage, which keeps helps wearer's feet dry faster, keeps the shoes light, and prolongs the lifespan of the material. Additionally, most people do not wear socks with water shoes

Clogs are a type of footwear made in part or completely from wood. Clogs are used worldwide and although the form may vary by culture, within a culture the form often remained unchanged for centuries. Traditional clogs remain in use as protective footwear in agriculture and in some factories and mines. Although clogs are sometimes negatively associated with cheap and folkloric footwear of farmers and the working class, some types of clogs are considered fashion wear today, such as Swedish trskor or Japanese geta

Mule is a style of shoe that has no back or constraint around the foot's heel. Mules have a history going as back as Ancient Rome, even though they were not popularly worn until sixteenth-century Europe. There, mules were bedroom slippers and not worn in public. Through the centuries, mules have changed in style and purpose and are no longer just boudoir shoes but are worn at any time, for any occasion. In addition to Western examples, mules come from cultures such as Turkey and Egypt, and appear in popular culture, from famous paintings to iconic celebrities' shoes

Espadrilles (Spanish: alpargatas, Catalan: espardenya, Basque: espartinak), are casual, rope-soled, flat, but sometimes high-heeled shoes. They usually have a canvas or cotton fabric upper and a flexible sole made of esparto rope. The esparto rope sole is the defining characteristic of an espadrille. The uppers vary widely in style
